      <hedline>
        <hl1>Windmills, Energy And Aesthetics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Cheryl Long letter disagrees with Bill McKibben's argument (Feb 16 Op-Ed) that we should allow wind plants in or near wild places like Adirondack Park</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I disagree with Bill McKibben's argument that we should allow wind plants in or near wild places like the Adirondack Park.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I disagree with Bill McKibben's argument that we should allow wind plants in or near wild places like the Adirondack Park.</p>
        <p>Yes, we must act quickly to address global warming, and yes, wind power can be a major part of that solution. But it is vital to the human spirit for us to have wild places near us. It's an essential way in which we can measure the effects of our behaviors upon the web of life that ultimately sustains us all.</p>
        <p>Here in Kansas, the wind power controversy is swirling in the beautiful Flint Hills. Every time I visit them, I am struck by what a difference the absence of roads and electric lines and other human construction makes to my experience.</p>
        <p>We must shift to renewable energy sources, but we can do it without intruding on ever more precious wild places.</p>
        <p>Cheryl Long  Topeka, Kan., Feb. 16, 2005</p>
      </block>
